docs.abstract: China’s practice of breaking into American computers has become a core grievance of the Trump administration as leaders of the two nations prepare to meet.
docs.snippet: China’s practice of breaking into American computers has become a core grievance of the Trump administration as leaders of the two nations prepare to meet.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Three years ago, President Barack Obama struck a deal with China that few thought was possible: President Xi Jinping agreed to end his nation’s yearslong practice of breaking into the computer systems of American companies, military contractors and government agencies to obtain designs, technology and corporate secrets, usually on behalf of China’s state-owned firms.

headline.main: After a Hiatus, China Accelerates Cyberspying Efforts to Obtain U.S. Technology
headline.print_headline: Chinese Cyberthieves Step Up Efforts to Snag U.S. Technology

docs.abstract: In 2016, when his company was negotiating a potential deal in Moscow, Donald J. Trump suggested that there was no need for the United States to penalize Russia over Crimea.
docs.snippet: In 2016, when his company was negotiating a potential deal in Moscow, Donald J. Trump suggested that there was no need for the United States to penalize Russia over Crimea.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In late March 2016, steaming toward the Republican nomination and with his aides still secretly in talks for a real estate deal in Russia, Donald J. Trump made a lengthy case for giving President Vladimir V. Putin what he wanted most: relief from American-led sanctions for his annexation of Crimea.

headline.main: Did a Real Estate Project Influence Trump’s View of Russia Sanctions?
headline.print_headline: New Relevance for Call to Ease Up on the Russians

docs.abstract: While Republicans cite the Supreme Court brawl as a factor in some Senate wins, Democrats say the fight did little damage and helped in the House.
docs.snippet: While Republicans cite the Supreme Court brawl as a factor in some Senate wins, Democrats say the fight did little damage and helped in the House.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Republicans saw the poisonous fight over Brett M. Kavanaugh’s Supreme Court confirmation as pure gold in the midterm elections, calling it “Kavanaugh’s Revenge.” Senator Bob Casey saw it a little differently in his own re-election bid — as a less-than-decisive issue in what was supposed to be a marquee race.

headline.main: ‘Kavanaugh’s Revenge’ Fell Short Against Democrats in the Midterms
headline.print_headline: Democrats See Benefits From Fight Against Kavanaugh

docs.abstract: John R. Bolton, the national security adviser, said the North’s lack of progress on ending its nuclear program left room for a new meeting, likely in early 2019, to be productive.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump plans to hold a second summit meeting early next year with Kim Jong-un, even though North Korea has failed to follow through with promises to start dismantling its nuclear weapons program, John R. Bolton, the national security adviser, said on Tuesday.

headline.main: Trump to Meet With Kim Jong-un, Despite North Korea’s Lapses, Bolton Says
headline.print_headline: Trump Will Meet Again With Kim, Despite North Korea’s Lapses, Bolton Says

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court unanimously ruled on Tuesday that an appeals court must take a fresh look at whether the Fish and Wildlife Service had gone too far in its attempt to protect an endangered species, the dusky gopher frog.

docs.abstract: The death of George Bush has quieted a raucous political system as it honors him for a civility it no longer possesses. But history shows that’s unlikely to last.
docs.snippet: The death of George Bush has quieted a raucous political system as it honors him for a civility it no longer possesses. But history shows that’s unlikely to last.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Just weeks after a bitterly fought election swept Democrats into power in Congress, a Republican president known for reaching across the aisle passed away. Leaders of both parties paid tribute to his civility and bipartisanship, saying the country could use more of that. And then within days of the burial, they went back to their partisan wars.

headline.main: A Kinder, Gentler Nation? Maybe for a Few Days
headline.print_headline: A Kinder, Gentler Nation? Maybe for a Few Days

docs.abstract: “Why would I take it off the table?” the president said of a pardon for Paul Manafort, who he said had been treated poorly by prosecutors for the special counsel.
docs.snippet: “Why would I take it off the table?” the president said of a pardon for Paul Manafort, who he said had been treated poorly by prosecutors for the special counsel.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Escalating his attacks on the special counsel investigation, President Trump said on Wednesday that a presidential pardon for his former campaign chairman Paul Manafort is “not off the table,” casting him and other subjects of the inquiry as victims of prosecutorial abuse.

headline.main: Trump Talks of Pardon for Manafort and Escalates Attacks on Russia Inquiry
headline.print_headline: Trump Raises  Idea of Pardon For Manafort
